<paper id="1578007245"><title>The FaCT System</title><year>1998</year><authors><author org="University of Manchester" id="2010142017">Ian Horrocks</author></authors><n_citation>287</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>80737574</reference><reference>1512262469</reference><reference>1536088796</reference><reference>1575501166</reference><reference>1593443951</reference><reference>1605860778</reference><reference>1605911328</reference><reference>1984720830</reference><reference>1995656639</reference><reference>2015932695</reference><reference>2057361103</reference><reference>2094309656</reference><reference>2145465694</reference><reference>2154362535</reference><reference>2296369602</reference></references><venue id="1183852906" type="C">Theorem Proving with Analytic Tableaux and Related Methods</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-69778-0_30</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.43628">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.62322">T-norm fuzzy logics</keyword><keyword weight="0.60984">Accessibility relation</keyword><keyword weight="0.44012">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.53439">Automated theorem proving</keyword><keyword weight="0.52564">Satisfiability</keyword><keyword weight="0.54948">Propositional calculus</keyword><keyword weight="0.55031">Description logic</keyword><keyword weight="0.4519">Algorithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.59814">Modal logic</keyword><keyword weight="0.50725">Backtracking</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>FaCT is a Description Logic classifier which has been implemented as a test-bed for a highly optimised tableaux satisfiability (subsumption) testing algorithm. The correspondence between modal and description logics also allows FaCT to be used as a theorem prover for the propositional modal logics K, KT, K4 and S4. Empirical tests have demonstrated the effectiveness of the optimised implementation and, in particular, of the dependency directed backtracking 